---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import CTASection from '../../components/CTASection.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  lang="en"
  slug="about"
  title="About / Why I Built This"
  description="Why CanteraPro exists: built by a rock yard worker who watched solo landscapers and small crews get priced out of business software that wasn't built for them."
>
  <section class="section page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">About CanteraPro</span>
      <h1>I built this because I watch this exact problem every single day.</h1>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container about-content">
      <p>
        I work at a rock yard, and tech is my hobby. Every day, solo landscapers and small crews pull in to load up
        mulch, gravel, decomposed granite — whatever the job calls for. I talk to these guys all
        day, every day. I hear about their jobs, their headaches, their busy seasons. And over
        time, one thing became obvious: almost none of them had a good way to actually run their
        business.
      </p>
      <p>
        They were writing estimates on the back of a receipt, texting invoices as a paragraph,
        trying to remember which client still owed them money. Some of them had tried the "real"
        business apps — the ones built for companies running 10, 20, 50 trucks — and gotten stuck
        paying $25, $50, sometimes close to $80 a month for a pile of features a one-truck
        operation is never going to touch. That's real money out of a guy's pocket every single
        month, just to write an invoice.
      </p>
      <p>
        And there was something else these apps almost all got wrong: language. A huge share of
        the hardest-working people in this trade are part of the Hispanic community, and a lot of
        them are still learning English. Nearly every piece of landscaping business software out
        there is built English-first, with maybe a half-hearted translation bolted on somewhere
        if you're lucky. I see the work ethic of this community up close, every single day at the
        yard — and it didn't sit right with me that the software meant to help them run their
        businesses barely spoke their language.
      </p>
      <p>
        So I built CanteraPro. "Cantera" is Spanish for a rock yard — it's a name that comes
        straight from where this idea started. The goal was simple: build something that actually
        serves solo landscapers and small crews. Something that doesn't cost a fortune, doesn't
        lock you into a subscription just to send an invoice, doesn't require an internet
        connection to work in the field, and treats Spanish as a first-class language, not an
        afterthought.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's also why the founding-member lifetime pricing exists. I wanted a way to reward the
        people who believe in this early — the ones taking a chance on a smaller, independent app
        instead of the big incumbents — with a price that will never come back once those spots
        are gone.
      </p>
      <p>
        I'm not a giant software company. I'm someone who sees this trade up close every day and
        wanted to build the tool I kept watching people need. If CanteraPro makes your week a
        little easier, that's exactly what it's for.
      </p>

      <div class="callout about-callout">
        <Icon name="leaf" size={22} />
        <p>Thanks for checking it out — I hope it earns a spot on your home screen.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTASection
    lang="en"
    heading="Give it a try."
    subheading="Free to start, no account required."
    primaryLabel="Download Now"
    primaryHref={`${base}en/download/`}
    secondaryLabel="See Features"
    secondaryHref={`${base}en/features/`}
  />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-hero {
    padding-top: var(--space-8);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
  .about-content {
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  .about-callout {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
  }
  .about-callout p {
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
